<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,190,1106]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,312,383,409]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[327,600,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[327,600,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Tuberculobasis inversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Selys" box="[819,968,384,410]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1876) Synopsis des Agrionines, 5 me legion: Agrion (suite). Le genre Agrion Bulletin de l´Academie royale de Belgique, (2) 41, 247 - 322, 496 - 539, 1233 - 1309 [1 - 282 reprint]." type="journal article" year="1876">
Selys (
<number box="[899,960,384,410]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1876.0">1876</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
based on a single male from Santarém, Pará, 
<collectingCountry box="[219,295,422,448]" name="Brazil" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[306,472,422,448]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1961) &quot; Leptobasis tuberculata &quot; SP. N. e notas sobre &quot; Leptobasis vacillans &quot; Selys, 1877 (Coenagriidae, Odonata). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 21 (2), 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1961">
Santos (
<number box="[402,463,422,448]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1961.0">1961</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described and illustrated both sexes of 
<taxonomicName box="[943,1214,423,448]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis box="[943,1214,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Leptobasis tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Porto Velho, Rondônia, 
<collectingCountry box="[281,353,461,487]" name="Brazil" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Brazil</collectingCountry>
but after examining the 
<typeStatus box="[647,750,461,487]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[791,908,461,486]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[791,908,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. inversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName box="[1081,1248,461,486]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis box="[1081,1248,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos, 1965" authorityName="Santos" authorityYear="1965" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[1317,1436,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. inversa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[159,319,500,526]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1965) Contribuicao ao conhecimento dos &quot; odonata &quot; da Regiao de Pocos de Caldas, MG. Minagrion gen. n., para Telagrion mecistogastrum Selys-Longchamp, 1865, com a descricao de uma nova especie (Odonata: Coenagriidae). Atas da Sociedade de Biologia do Rio de Janeiro, 9 (1), 8 - 12." type="journal article" year="1965">
Santos, 
<number box="[255,319,500,526]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1965.0">1965</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[393,496,500,526]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">holotype</typeStatus>
lacks head and right wings, but color is well preserved. The descriptions made by 
<bibRefCitation author="Selys" box="[190,347,538,564]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1876) Synopsis des Agrionines, 5 me legion: Agrion (suite). Le genre Agrion Bulletin de l´Academie royale de Belgique, (2) 41, 247 - 322, 496 - 539, 1233 - 1309 [1 - 282 reprint]." type="journal article" year="1876">
Selys (
<number box="[274,338,538,564]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1876.0">1876</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[408,580,538,564]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1961) &quot; Leptobasis tuberculata &quot; SP. N. e notas sobre &quot; Leptobasis vacillans &quot; Selys, 1877 (Coenagriidae, Odonata). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 21 (2), 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1961">
Santos (
<number box="[508,571,538,564]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1961.0">1961</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
are adequate. Until recently the only illustrations known for females specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[304,419,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[304,419,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. inversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were those provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[718,885,577,603]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1961) &quot; Leptobasis tuberculata &quot; SP. N. e notas sobre &quot; Leptobasis vacillans &quot; Selys, 1877 (Coenagriidae, Odonata). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 21 (2), 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1961">
Santos (
<number box="[814,875,577,603]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1961.0">1961</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
under 
<emphasis box="[969,1144,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[969,1141,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">L. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
I had the opportunity to study and provide an illustration of the thoracic structures of a specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1081,1135,616,642]" name="Peru" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Peru</collectingCountry>
that agreed well with the specimen described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[431,599,654,680]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1961) &quot; Leptobasis tuberculata &quot; SP. N. e notas sobre &quot; Leptobasis vacillans &quot; Selys, 1877 (Coenagriidae, Odonata). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 21 (2), 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1961">
Santos (
<number box="[528,590,654,680]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1961.0">1961</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
especially on the unique shape of the hind prothoracic lobe (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1423,654,680]" captionStart="FIGURES 47 – 54" captionStartId="20.[151,272,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[188,1374,193,1754]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[180,1408,117,1857]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 47 – 54. Tuberculobasis female thorax, in dorsal view: T. cardinalis, holotype (47); T. costalimai, allotype (48); T. inversa, Peru, Loreto (49); T. mammilaris, Venezuela (50); T. tirio, allotype (51); T. williamsoni, allotype (52); T. yanomami, paratype (53), and in dorso-lateral view: Tuberculobasis sp. 1, Manaus, Amazonas (54) [47 by N. von Ellenrieder; 50, 53 by J. De Marmels]." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/187815/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number box="[1389,1423,654,680]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="49.0">49</number>
</figureCitation>
). R.W. Garrison identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[480,595,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[480,595,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. inversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a male in his collection found in the same month and at the same place where the female illustrated herein had been collected and suggested, and I agree, that it is the female of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">T. inversa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, the Peruvian specimen has a pair of small but very evident mesepisternal tubercles that are apparently lacking in the Brazilian specimen described by Santos. I believe these small tubercle might have been overlooked by 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos" box="[394,560,848,874]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" refString="Santos, N. D. (1961) &quot; Leptobasis tuberculata &quot; SP. N. e notas sobre &quot; Leptobasis vacillans &quot; Selys, 1877 (Coenagriidae, Odonata). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 21 (2), 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1961">
Santos (
<number box="[490,551,848,874]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1961.0">1961</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
as he did with the tubercles of the females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1114,1267,848,873]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[1114,1267,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Remarks under 
<taxonomicName box="[227,381,887,912]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[227,381,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Besides, by its male character 
<emphasis box="[774,795,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[805,891,886,912]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">inversa</taxonomicName>
belongs in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1076,1200,887,912]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[1076,1200,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group in which the known females (
<emphasis box="[349,695,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[349,505,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">T. costalimai</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[518,686,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="williamsoni">T. williamsoni</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
have tubercles, whereas the known females (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[1236,1402,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mammilaris">T.mammilaris</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tirio">T. tirio</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[257,408,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yanomami">
<emphasis box="[257,408,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. yanomami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) of the 
<taxonomicName box="[499,639,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mammilaris">
<emphasis box="[499,639,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">mammilaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group the known females (
<emphasis box="[958,1220,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[958,1130,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mammilaris">T. mammilaris</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1141,1220,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tirio">T. tirio</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1276,1426,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yanomami">
<emphasis box="[1276,1426,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. yanomami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) have no tubercles. In the 
<taxonomicName box="[445,567,1002,1027]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[445,567,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group 
<taxonomicName box="[741,856,1002,1027]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Tuberculobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inversa">
<emphasis box="[741,856,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. inversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily separated from the other species by its subparallel mesepisternal tubercles, with anterior borders connected to mesostigmal plate by a curved plate (
<figureCitation box="[159,303,1080,1106]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 34" captionStartId="18.[151,270,1973,1997]" captionTargetBox="[327,1275,181,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[312,1277,161,1944]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 34. Tuberculobasis, male thorax in dorsal and lateral view in T. arara, holotype (25, 26); T. costalimai, holotype (27, 28); T. guarani, holotype (29, 30); T. inversa, holotype (31, 32); T. williamsoni, holotype (33, 34)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/187813/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Figs. 
<number box="[226,303,1080,1106]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="31.32">31, 32</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
